50–1417":"1350–1417","1300–Male":"1300–Deceased","1337":"1337","1325":"1325","1300":"1300","about 1325":"about 1325","1453":"1453","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1417":"1417","1328":"1328","Rishton, Lancashire, England":"Rishton, Lancashire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Rishton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Rushton  . Early bearers: Aleander Rishton, 1560 in   IGI   (Great Harwood, Lancs); Anna Rishton, 1598, Elizabeth Rushton, 1635 in   IGI   (Altham, Lancs); Robert Rishton, 1603, James Rushton, 1627, Robert Riston, 1757 in   IGI   (Colne, Lancs)."],"variants":[{"name":"Rushton","meanings":["English: habitational name from Rishton (Lancashire) and Rushton (Staffordshire), and perhaps also from Rushton (Cheshire, Northamptonshire), Rushton in East Stoke (Dorset), and Rhiston (Shropshire). The placenames derive from Old English <i>risc</i> ‘rush’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’."]},{"name":"IGI","meanings":["1  English: (i) perhaps a variant of   Garth   with loss of  <i>-r-</i> before the final consonant. Compare Thomas Gath, 1600, John Garth, 1619 in   IGI   (Saint Keyne, Cornwall); Nicholas Gath, 1716, Thomas Garth, 1726 in   IGI   (Saint Breward, Cornwall). (ii) alternatively, a variant of   Goth   with unrounding of the vowel, if not vice versa.","2  Irish: from  <b>Mag Eochadha</b>,  see  McGough  ."]},{"name":"Riston","meanings":["English: habitational name from Long Riston (East Yorkshire), North and South Reston (Lincolnshire), and East and Sco Ruston (Norfolk). The placenames derive from Old English <i>hrīs</i> ‘brushwood’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. The name may sometimes have been confused with   Ritson  .","English: occasional variant of   Rushton  .","Scottish: habitational name from Reston in Coldingham (Berwickshire), cognate with 1 above."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Attainment’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705192,"age":3,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":12,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":57,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation 